THIS INCIDNET ACTUALLY OCCURRED WHILE ENROUTE FROM THE SHIPPER TO DALLAS, T X. THIS CHEMICAL CARRIES A SECONDARY CLASSIFICATION OF "CORROSIVE". column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: AFTER STOPPING AT PORT OF ENTRY DRIVER PROCEEDED TO CHECK HIS LOAD, HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID COMING OUT THE REAR DOORS.  THE DRIVER OPENED THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER AND POURED ABSORBENT MATERIAL AT THE REAR TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE TRAILER IS EQUIPPED WITH A STEEL PAN FOR SECONDARY CONTAINMENT TO KEEP A SPILL FROM SOAKING THROUGH THE FLOOR. AFTER STOPPING THE MATERIAL FROM EXITING THE TRAILER THE DRIVER CALLED ENSCO.  HE WAS TOLD TO CALL THE GENERATOR AND ASK FOR THEIR ASSISTANCE.  TH COLORADO STATE POLICE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DIVISION WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. THE STATE PATROL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL OFFICER ASKED THE DRIVER TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO AN ISOLATED AREA OF THE TRUCK STOP AND AWAIT THE ARRIVAL OF THE RESPONSE TEAM. THE RESPONSE TEAM REMOVED ALL THE DRUMS FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND PLACED THEM ON A PLASTIC SHEET.  EACH DRUM WAS CLEANED WITH A SOLVENT, THE DRUM WHICH CAUSED THE SPILL WAS FOUND TO HAVE HAD A SPLIT AT THE BOTTOM.  THERE WAS NO APPARENT CAUSE FOR THIS FAILURE. THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED AS WELL AS ALL THE DRUMS.  THE TRAILER WAS RELOADED AND ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN OVERPACKS AND MANIFESTED TO ENSCO FOR INCINERATION. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED IN THE TRAILER.  OF THIS AMOUNT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND.  AFTER THE SOIL HAD BEEN DUG UP AND THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED THE STATE PATROL OFFICER RELEASED THE UNIT.

column168: 1. SPILL INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF A CARGO TRANSFER FROM THE TANK-TRAILER TO A 25,000 BBL STORAGE TANK.  AN IN-LINE CUSTODY TRANSFER PUMP PULLS FLUID FROM THE TRAILER THROUGH HOSE AND PIPING AND MOVES IT VIA ADDITIONAL PIPING INTO THE TANK.  PUMP RATE IS 400 BBLS PER HOUR. 2. IN THE TWO DAYS PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT, LOADS TO THE TERMINAL HAD DOUBLED DUE TO INCREASED PRODUCTION AT THE TRUNKLINE PLANT.  STORAGE CAPACITY WAS STRETCHED.  DUE TO POOR COMUNICATION AT THE TERMINAL BETWEEN THE DRIVERS AND GAUGERS, FLUID LEVEL IN THE TANK WAS NOT RELATED TO THE DRIVER UNLOADING AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. 3. AS THE DRIVER NEARED COMPLETION OF UNLOADING, HE HEARD FLUID HIT THE GROUND NEXT TO THE TANK.  THE TRANSFER PUMP WAS SHUT OFF IMMEDIATELY, BUT WITH THE LARGE SURFACE AREA OF THE FLUID IN TANK, CONSIDERABLE OIL SPILLED OVER THROUGH THE HATCH AND TANK VENTS.  TWENTY-FIVE BARRELS IS JUST 3/8" BY GAUGE IN THE TANK. 4. THE SPILL WAS CONFINED ENTIRELY INSIDE THE TANK FIREWALL DIKE. TWENTY-THREE BARRELS WAS SUCTIONED BY VACUUM TRUCK FROM THE GROUND SURFACE AND PUMPED TO AN ADJACENT TANK.  MANIFOLD VALVES WERE OPENED TO DRAIN THE FULL TANK AND EQUALIZE WITH THE ADJACENT TANK. 55. CLEAN-UP CONSISTED OF MOPING RESIDUAL OIL WITH ABSORBENT PADS. CONTAMINATED TOP SOIL WAS SHAVED TO A 2" DEPTH AND REPLACED WITH 28 YEARDS OF FIL DIRT.  THE STORAGE TANK WAS WASHED WHERE STAINED. 6. REMEDIAL ACTION INVOLVES OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES FOR LOGGING OF LOADS TO A CONTINUATION SHEET KEPT IN A MAILBOX NEAR THE TRANSFER PUMP.  EACH LOAD ACCOUNTS FOR 7" OF FLUID RISE IN THE STORAGE TANK.  TANK LEVEL IS CALCULATED AGAINIST THE PRIOR TANK GAUGE.  WHEN LEVEL REACHES HALF FULL, TANK GAUGES ARE INCREASED TO TWICE PER SHIFT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 PM, JUNE 26, 1989, PASSING TRAIN REPORTED TANK CAR UCLX 3028 LEAKING PRODUCT IN AMARILLO YARD TRACK 0204.  CAR WAS MOVED TO ZETA AND RESPONSE TEAM FROM VULCAN MATERIALS, WITCHITA, TRANSFERRED LOAD TO UCLX 3067.  SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND HAZ-MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY HANDLED SOIL REMOVAL AND TESTING.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT SHIPING POINT TO LOAD.  THE LOADER DIRECTED HIM TO THE PROPER LOCATION AND OUR DRIVER SPOTTED HIS UNIT.  THE LOADER PLACED A HOSE IN THE DOME OF THE TRAILER AND STARTED TO TRANSFER PRODUCT TO OUR TRAILER.  THE HOSE WAS NOT SECURED AND WAS JUMPING. OUR DRIVER BROUGHT THIS TO THE ATTENTION OF THE LOADER WHO RESPONDED THAT IT WAS NOTHING TO WORRY ABOUT.  A SHORT TIME LATER THE HOSE JUMPED OUT OF THE DOME OPENING AND A SPILL OCCURRED.  THE LOADER SHUT DOWN THE LOADING OPERATION AND TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT HIS DESTINATION FOR DELIVERY.  HE HOOKED UP HIS PUMP TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  HE ENGAGED HIS PUMP AND A SHORT TIME LATER MATERIAL STARTED TO OVERFLOW HIS TRAILER.  HE SHUT DOWN AS SOON AS POSSIBLE AND REPORTED THE SPILL.  IT WAS FOUND THAT HE HAD HOOKED UP HIS PUMP IN REVERSE AND INSTEAD OF TRANSFERING THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE HE WAS PUMPING MATERIAL FROM STORAGE TO HIS TRAILER CAUSING THE OVERFLOW.  OUR DRIVER CORRECTED HIS MISTAKE AND PROCEEDED TO COMPLETE HIS DELIVERY. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AREA.

OUR TRAILER HAD BEEN SPOTTED AT A RAIL SIDING FOR LOADING FOR LATER DELIVERY.  AFTER LOADING AND WHILE SPOTTED THE TRAILER BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AS WELL AS OUR PERSONNEL WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE MATERIAL WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE RAIL CAR IN ORDER TO LIMIT THE LOSS OF MATERIAL.  IT WAS DETERMINIED THAT THE RUBBER LINING HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ATTACK THE METAL.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIR.  WE ENGAGED A CONTRACTOR TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL AREA.
CUSTOMER VALVE ON TANK (PC VALVE) CAME LOOSE AND PRODUCT FLOWED OVER TANK AND A FEW DROPS ON THE GROUND
GEAR PUMP SEAL LEAKING. DRIVER SWITCHED OVER TO COMPRESSOR AND FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT ANY PROBLEMS.

DRIVER REVERSED HOSES ON PRODUCT PUMP CAUSING SPILLAGE.  SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED IMMEDIATELY AND A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED.  THE PRODUCT DID NOT REACH ANY WATERWAYS AND ALL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

WHEN PILLUNG EHEEL BACK TO POSITION ON FOUR WHEELS THE DRUM SLIPPED.  THE DRUM SLIPPED AND WAS PUNCTURED WITH THE BLADES OF THE BARREL WHEELER.  PUNCTURE APPROXIMATELY 4" FROM TOP OF DRUM.  DRIVER ROLLED THE DRUM AND WHEELER UNTIL PUNCTURES WERE FACING UP TO REDUCE LEAKING.  THEN UPRIGHTED AFTER PULLING WHEELS LOOSE FROM DRUM.

DRIVER WAS LEAVING LYNCHBURG, VA (11:00AM) WHEN HE NOTICED A STRONG SMELL AFTER ENTERING THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK.  AFTER ISOLATING THE TRUCK THE DRIVER NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISORS OF WHAT HE THOUGHT HAD SPILLED. SUPERVISORS INFORMED HIM OF THE POTENTIAL HEALTH HAZARDS OF CHLOROFORM AND TOLD HIM TO KEEP UNNECESSSARY PEOPLE AS WELL AS HIMSELF AWAY FROM THE TRUCK, TO STAY UPWIND, OUT OF LOW AREAS, AND WHAT EMERGENCY ACTION STEPS TO TAKE. CHEMTREC WAS THEN NOTIFIED FOLLOWED BY ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS, INC. LOCATED IN ROCKY MOUNT, VA -- THE CLOSEST COMPANY LOCATED TO LYNCHBURG. ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS CAME OUT TO INSPECT THE TRUCK. CLOSER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT TOO MUCH HEAVY FREIGHT WAS LOAEED ON TOP OF THIS PRODUCT, ULTIMATELY CRUSHING THE CAN INSIDE.  TO PREVENT RECURRENCE THE LOADERS WILL BE ADVISED OF THIS INCIDENT AND GOOD LOADING PRACTICES.  THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS AN EXAMPLE OF WHAT CAN HAPPEN AND THE AMOUNT OF DOLLARS INVOLVED DUE TO LOADING HEAVY ITEMS ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

GATX 9548 WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A LOOSE PACKING GLAND NUT, LOOSE LIQUID VALVE AND VAPOR VALVE PLUGS. DAVIS TIGHTENED ALL LOOSE FITTINGS WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR LEAK.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: EMPLOYEE, DAVID BUSHNELL, LOADED 7224 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM ODISTALLATE AT CANAL REFINING IN CHURCH POINT, LA.  UPON ENTERING THE HIGHWAY HE NOTICED A SMALL LEAKAGE. UPON INSPECTION HE DISCOVERED THAT THE CLEAN-OUT PLUG TO THE TANK HAD LOOSENED AND APROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD SPILLED. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO WITHIN 100 YARDS ON THE HIGHWAY.  A CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED.  (SAND WAS SPREAD ONTHE HIGHWAY).  DEQ AND THE LA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPT. WERE NOTIFIED. NEITHER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON THE DATE 6/23/90, AT APPROXIMATELY 00:56 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS (HAZ-MAT COORDINATOR ) AND FRANCIS VANCE (HAZ-MAT SPECIALIST), WERE DISPATCHED TO GATE C-23 OF OUR AIRPORT FACILITIES.  THE REPORT WAS AN ODOR ON THE MAIN DECK OF OUR YS-11 (914AX).  ENROUTE, I CALLED HAZ-MAT BASE TO DISPATCH OUR CFR TEAM FOR BACK-UP.  WHEN I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, I TALKED TO THE GROUND CREW TO SEE IF ANYONE WAS FEELING ILL EFFECT AND ALSO TO GET SOME IDEA OF WHAT THE ODOR RESEMBLED.  I WAS ADVISED BY MICHELE SPENCE (RAMP LOADER) TAHT THE ODOR WAS SLIGHT.  THEY HAD ALREADY UNLOADED THE CONTAINER CONTAINING ALL OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ON BOARD THIS FLIGHT AND SHE THOUGHT SHE NOTICED THE SAME ODOR COMING FROMIT.  I THEN ISOLATED THE CONTAINER AND WENT UP TO THE COCKPIT TO GET THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATIONS. THERE WAS ONLY ONE COMMODITY IN THE CONTAINER OTHER THAN DRY ICE.  IT WAS AMYL METHYL KETONE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1110.  I THEN WENT TO THE CARGO MAIN DECK AND WAS UNABLE TO NOTICE ANY ODOR.  BY THIS TIME, APPROXIMATELY 01:15, MRS. VANCE AND MARVIN CORBIN (SAFETY SPECIALIST) WERE DONNED IN FIRE TURNOUT GEAR AND SCBA'S.  I INSTRUCTED THEM TO OPEN THE HAZ-MAT CONTAINER, FIND THE LEAKING SHIPMENT, PUT IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM, EMULSIFY, AND CLEAN UP ANY SPILLED PRODUCT.  BRUCE CUNNINGHAM (SAFETY SPECIALIST), MIKE BOLDMAN (SAFETY SPECIALIST), JIM CURTIS (HAZ-MAT) SUPERVISOR), AND I WAS STANDING BY AS BACK-UP WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER.  MR. CUNNINGHAM, MR. BOLDMAN, AND MR. CURTIS WERE DONNED IN FIRE TURN-OUT GEAR.  SHIPMENT IDENTIFIED AS TRI 653273316 PHB. CONTAINING AMYL METHYL KETONE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1110 WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. THSI WAS A TWO-PIECE SHIPEMENT.  TWO STEEL DOT 17-E DRUMS, 5 GALLONS EACH. ONE STEEL DOT-17-E DRUM LEAKING AROUND THE THREADED CAP.  THERE WAS A PLASTIC SEALING DEVICE OVER THE THREADED CAP.  CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS UNDETERMINED.  THE STEEL DRUM WAS UNDAMAGED.  BOTH DRUMS WERE PROPERLY MARKED WITH THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME AND UN1110.  THEY WERE BOTH LABELED WITH SPECIFICATION ORIENTATION ARROWS AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABELS. PROPERLY PREPARED SHIPPERS DECLARATION WAS ATTACHED TO SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ-MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.  IT WILL BE MOVED VIA ABX TODESTINATION IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM TELEPHONE CONVERSATION WITH HIM AT 12:25 HRS. ON 6/25/90.

DISCOVERED LEAKING IN YARD.  SAFETY MAN, MARLIN TURNER CAME TO TERMINAL AND BACKED TRAILER INTO DOCK.  WE APPLIED FLOOR DRY AND MOVED THE LEAKING DRUM TO SALVAGE DRUM.  DELIVERED SALVAGE DRUM TO CONSIGNEE.

THE FOLLOWING REPORT WAS PREPARED BY L. DIAZ, MARINE OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR:  APPARENTLY, WHEN THE SUN BOX WAS REMOVED, THE LEFT LEG, (LANDING GEAR) WHICH WAS SHORTER THAN THE OTHER, CAUSED THE TANK TO ROLL OVER ON ITS LEFT SIDE.  THERE WAS NO APPARENT DAMAGE TO THE INNER TANK WALL.  THE LEAKAGE OBSERVED WAS AROUND TWO UPPER VENTS.  THIS LEAK STOPPED WHEN THE TANK WAS RIGHTED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR TRANSPORT WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE AT THE AMOCO STATION UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK IN MICHIGAN CITY, INDIANA.  AT THAT POINT AND TIME, A LADY, MRS. PIERCE, CAME IN TO PUMP GAS IN HER VEHICLE.  AFTER THE LADY FILLED HER VEHICLE, SHE STARTED TO BACK UP TOWARD OUR TRANSPORT.  WITHIN A FEW FEET OF BACKING, SHE NOTICED THAT SHE HAD HIT OUR UNLOADING HOSE AND BROKE IT LOOSE FROM THE UNDERGROUND TANK SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS.  THE FIRE DEPT; POLICE AND HAMAT TEAMS WERE CALLED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE. THE STREET DEPARTMENT THEN PUT SAND ON THE SPILLED GASOLINE, SOAKING IT UP.  THE SAND THEN WAS CLEANED UP AND TAKEN TO THE STREET DEPARTMENT IN MICHIGAN CITY TO AIR OUT.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS LOADED OUT OF DALLAS 461 ON TRL DUM21-6533 AND CLOSED 6/16/90 RAN FROM 461 TO 269.  6/17/90 DRIVER, GORDON RAPER NOTICED THE LEAK.  APPARENTLY HE IN TURN CALLED LEE YANCEY, MEMPHIS 269 LINE DISPATCH. LEE HANDLED WITH TEXAS DEPT OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND THE WINFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT.  CHIEF MCRAY TALKED TO MEMPHIS LINE AND ADVISED THEM TO CONTACT CHEM TRAC.  WHICH THEY DID.  LOAD WAS WORKED AT THE SITE UNTIL THE LEAKING PAIL WAS LOCATED.  DRIVER BROUGHT LOAD BACK TO 461 FOR REWORKING. THIS LEAKING 5 GALLON PAIL WAS PLACED INSIDE SEVERAL TRASH BAGS THEN PUT INSIDE EMPTY 55 GALLON DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE DALLAS TERMINAL MONDAY PM BY EM TECH. CURRENT SATUS OF FREIGHT: IN RECOVERY DRUM AT 461 DOCK HOW INCIDENT CLEANED UP. BY WHOM. ACTION TAKEN SINCE: LEAKER PLACED IN PLASTIC BAGS AND INSIDE RECOVERY DRUM BY EM TECH CO. CONTACTED SHIPPER FOR AUTHORIZATION TO RETURN TO THEM FOR SALVAGE CREDIT. ACTION TAKEN RE: PERSON RESPONSIBLE: SAMMY TAYLOR. CHECK #517 THAT LOADED THIS SHPT AND SHIPMENTS AROUND IT HAS BEEN TERMINATED.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: ON 11-28-9, AT 0217, SORT SUPERVISOR LYNN POEPPELMAN CALLED AND REQUESTED THAT A HAZ-MAT SPILL TEAM COME TO DOOR Q-23 TO CHECK OUT A SHIPMENT IN A "C" CONTAINER.  SHE EXPLAINED THAT THE FIBREBOARD BOXEX HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE DRY ICE IN THEM.  THIS WAS DUE TO THE FROST ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGES.  THERE WAS SEVEN PIECES IN THIS SHIPMENT.  AT 0249, I, TONY FRYE AND A SPILL TEAM ARRIVED ON THE SCENE,  SPILL TEAM MEMBER, JEFF HOSTETLER, OPENED ONE OF THE FIBRE BOARD BOXES AND FOUND DRY ICE INSIDE AND A STEEL DRUM THAT COULD HOLD FIVE GALLONS.  THE STEEL DRUM CONTAINED "PENTAN 2.4 DIONE".  THIS WAS MARKED ON THE STEEL DRUM ALONG WIHT "UN2319" AND LABELED "FLAMMABLE LIQUID" WIHT A "CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY" HANDLING LABEL.  ONCE WE SAW THIS, THE SEVEN PIECES WERE TAKEN TO THE FREEZER DUE TO THE FACT THAT THEY WERE PACKED IN DRY ICE AND THERE WAS NO FLSH POINT LISTED ON THE STEEL DRUM.  ONCE BACK AT THE HAZ SORT, I, TONY FRYE, OPENED  VERY FIBREBOARD BOX, I FOUND IN ONE BOX ANOTHR STEEL CAN LABELED AS "FLAMMABLE LIQUID", WITH A "POISON SUNSIDIARY RISK LABEL" AND A "CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY" LABEL.  THIS WAS MARKED ON THE SEVEN PIECES IN THE SHIPMENT WAS PREPARED IDENTICAL TO THIS PEICE. ALSO ON THE THREE STELL DRUMS WAS THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: INFORMATION: IATA T3H AUTH GROSS WEIGHT 45KGS ITOH OPTICAL INDUSTRIES CO., LTD. 3-19 MIYANARI-CHO GAMABORI, AICHI, JAPAN. SHIPPER: MIKI AND CO., LTD. 3-15-5 NIHONHASHI  CHO-KV.  CONSIGNEE: MIKI SANGYO (UBA) INC.  747 THIRD AVE NEW YORK, NY 10017.  NOTE: THIS WAS HAND WRITTEN ON THE STEEL CAN, AN IATA T3H SPECIFICATION MARKING IS AUTHORIZED FOR A STEEL "JERRICAN".  THESE WERE STEEL DRUMS AND THERE WERE NO OTHER SPECIFICATION MARKINGS ON THE STEEL DRUMS.  THE AIRWAYBILL LISTED THE SHIPPER AS NIPPON EXPRESS AND CONSIGNEE AS SILOR OPTICAL OF FLORIDA.  SEE ATTACHED AIRWAYBILL.  THERE WAS NO MARKINGS OR LABELS ON HTE OUTSIDE OF THE FIBREBOARD BOXES.  ALOS, NO SHIPPERS DECLARATION ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT.  IN THEOTHER THREE PACKAGES WAS SOME COMPONENTS THAT ARE PART OF THIS SHIPMENT/  THIS SHIPMENT WAS SECURED ON A FREEZER AT THE ABX HAZ MAT SORT FACILITY TO BE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMRGENCY RESPONSE, R M STINE WAS CONTACTED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS (LEA MAKOVEC) THAT TANK CAR GATX 23048 HAD PRODDUCT SPLASHING FROM THE TOP WHILE BEING SWITCHED. CAR WAS ISOLATED FOR MR.  STINE'S INSPECTION.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THE "OSECO" FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED WITH LIKE DISC AND RELEASED CAR FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  CHEMTREC (JIM COOPER) KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT WERE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.
